year={2017},
number={210489},
pages={15-20},
doi={10.1201/9781315269184-4},
note={cited By 0; Conference of 5th International Congress on Interdisciplinary Behavior and Social Science, ICIBSOS 2016 ; Conference Date: 5 November 2016 Through 6 November 2016;  Conference Code:210489},
url={https://www.scopus.com/inward/record.uri?eid=2-s2.0-85046553893&doi=10.1201%2f9781315269184-4&partnerID=40&md5=da55230ca08b87f7fc9e8f50e012e507},
affiliation={Kaunas University of Technology, Kaunas, Lithuania},
abstract={In the European Union 49.6% of the whole food demand is being fulfilled by small and medium farmers. The developed Common Agriculture Policy (CAP) is aimed to guarantee the market for small and medium farmers; however, the government is obligated to also pay for the surplus. A large proportion of the food products are being exported to other markets at much lower prices, or are passing their expiry dates and are considered as waste. Due to this problem, the authors developed a case study of the European Union food industry by modeling different logistic network scenarios, and implemented a competitiveness strategy based on the Industry 4.0 concept and lean philosophy. The methodology of this paper consisted of literature analysis, specialist interview, and mathematical modeling by using Rstudio and simulated annealing algorithm. The authors’ results showed that by implementing a logistic cluster in the EU and by using the developed competitiveness strategy, a sustainable supply chain can be achieved, together with low management costs and visibility of the whole food chain. © 2017 Taylor & Francis Group.},
author_keywords={Food industry;  Industry 4.0;  Lean philosophy;  Logistic clusters;  Supply chain},
